import java.util.*;

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("A", "B", "C"));

        // Forgot to call next() before remove()
        Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
        while (it.hasNext()) {
            it.remove();  // ERROR!
        }
    }
}

phase2.explanation:
You can't call remove() without first calling next()!

remove() removes the element returned by the most recent next() call.

FIX: Always call next() before remove():
while (it.hasNext()) {
    String s = it.next();  // First! THEN remove
    it.remove();  // Safe
}

Or check a condition:
while (it.hasNext()) {
    String s = it.next();
    if (s.equals("B")) {
        it.remove();  // Remove only B
    }
}

Remember: next() → process → remove()

